<TEXT>
a bill to limit smoking in this tobacco state 
won preliminary approval in the house of delegates on monday but 
it is a weaker set of regulations than contained in legislation 
supported by health groups 
the bill would require establishment of nosmoking areas in 
state and local government buildings it would allow local 
governments to impose stricter rules against smoking but would 
limit local efforts to ban smoking in small businesses in theaters 
and on public transportation 
the bill passed in a voice vote monday and was due for a final 
house vote tuesday was approved over the objection of health 
lobbyists and legislators who backed a bill calling for stricter 
smoking regulation 
nevertheless some in the house worried about reaction in a 
state whose economy was built on tobacco 
seldom in my career have i built my own political gallows and 
provided the rope said delegate charles r hawkins a republican 
from tobaccogrowing pittsylvania county if i vote for this i 
might be doing that 
if its approved in the final house vote the bill would have to 
be reconciled with a more stringent bill recently approved by the 
senate 
in addition to requiring nosmoking areas in government 
buildings the bills main impact would be to set standards for 
local nosmoking ordinances 
local governments would be allowed to demand nosmoking areas in 
restaurants and ban smoking in elevators schools indoor service 
lines and school buses 
but local ordinances couldnt regulate smoking in businesses 
with less than 10000 square feet of floor space socalled mom 
and pop stores nor could they regulate smoking in privately owned 
meeting rooms in theaters or on public transportation 
the bill also doesnt address smoking in private work areas 
the rejected rival bill similar to that already approved by the 
senate would have allowed workers to declare their areas 
smokefree by a twothirds vote 
</TEXT>
