<TEXT>
president bush saying nobody wants to 
threaten the soviet union said monday that a united germany 
belongs inside nato but western forces might not be deployed in 
what is now east germany 
bush applauded what he called the bottom line spelled out by 
west german chancellor helmut kohl on the future of germany nato 
membership 
bush also expressed my appreciation of chairman mikhail s 
gorbachevs statesmanlike view that decisions regarding german 
unity should be left to the people of germany 
but the official east german news agency reported monday that 
gorbachev told east german leaders flatly that a united germany 
cannot belong to nato 
the news agency adn quoted gorbachev as telling hans modrow 
east germanys communist premier that he had clearly told kohl 
that a united germany staying within the structure of nato cannot 
be accepted 
national security adviser brent scowcroft said monday night 
thats not exactly what secretary of state james baker was 
told during his visit to moscow last week it was not really as 
positive as that scowcroft said after a state dinner for the 
president of the congo 
kohl said earlier that he had gotten the green light for 
unification from gorbachev during a weekend visit to moscow 
keeping germany inside nato would afford the most stability for 
both east and west in europe bush told a news conference 
us officials disclosed in ottawa that secretary of state james 
a baker iii had been discussing a us plan for the unification of 
germany with the foreign ministers of britain france west germany 
and the soviet union before and during his european trip 
the socalled twoplusfour plan would call for leaders of 
the east german government that emerges from march elections to 
meet west german leaders to make plans for the political legal and 
economic structures of the new country 
the two germanies operating as sovereign states also would 
have the power to determine the size of the german army 
afterward the united states the soviet union britain and 
france the big four victors over germany in world war ii 
would discuss such security issues as german membership in nato 
at the nato foreign ministers meeting in ottawa which eastern 
bloc countries are attending as observers baker took up the matter 
with his soviet counterpart eduard shevardnadze on monday and 
scheduled further talks with him on tuesday 
britain and france have endorsed the idea and the soviets are 
quite interested said a state department official who spoke on 
condition that he not be identified 
there might be some flexibility obviously on the deployment 
of nato forces inside what is now east germany bush said 
i think chancellor kohl is absolutely correct and we ought to 
support him nato membership said bush who will confer with 
kohl at camp david on feb 2425 
bush said nato membership for a new united germany is the 
most reassuring and stabilizing concept both for the west and 
in terms of how the eastern europeans will eventually look at it 
maybe not today 
theres some flexibility on deployment of nato forces into 
eastern europe nobody wants to threaten the soviet union said 
bush 
bush conferred this past weekend at camp david with nato 
secretary general manfred woerner who said afterwards that a way 
will be found to keep germany inside nato while recognizing the 
legitimate security interests of the soviet union 
one possibility woerner said would be not to extend natos 
military reach over the region that is now east germany 
asked if germany would be less threatening in an alliance rather 
than neutral bush said i think so the germans are good 
nato partners now and theyll be good nato partners then he said 
east germany is part of the warsaw pact 
bush said many europeans would be concerned by a neutral 
nonaligned germany its a concern that would be allayed by 
having a unified germany inside of nato said bush 
in ottawa meanwhile shevardnadze told a group of british 
correspondents i am not saying neutrality is the only way but 
it is the best way 
shevardnadze also said the big four might have to take up the 
issue of german reunification there is room for negotiation 
among the four powers shevardnadze said 
bush said he did not think a meeting of the four powers was 
needed at this juncture at some point clearly the four 
powers will have to have some say 
