<TEXT>
soviet submarines have illegally 
entered swedish waters in dramatically steppedup operations since 
mikhail gorbachev came to power according to a study released 
sunday 
in one case a soviet minisubmarine got as far as stockholm 
harbor coming within a mile of the neutralo countrys royal 
palace said the rand corp report strager than fiction soviet 
submarine operations in swedish waters 
despite what appears to be real soviet progress in domestic 
reform and arms control this is still going on and why the swedes 
continue to permit it i dont know said gordon h mccormick 
who wrote the report based on public documents and swedish sources 
the report was sponsored by the us air force 
the intrusions have harmed gorbachevs attempt to change his 
countrys image in the west but he is unlikely to scale back 
operations unless he can demonstrate they are causing greater 
difficulties for the soviet union in the west than has been the 
case so far mccormick said 
soviet submarines have penetrated swedish waters since world war 
ii but before the 1980s there were never more than four probable 
intrusions a year and those usually involved one submarine at a 
time in outer coastal waters the report said 
since 1980 swedish sources indicate that an average rate of 
between 17 and 36 foreign operations are being conducted per year 
depending on the degree of probability that is assigned to each 
underwater contact the report said 
in addition the new operations utilized multiple submarines 
minisubs and combat swimmers and penetrated much deeper into 
swedens coastal defense zones including harbors of major naval 
bases the report said 
some intrusions made international headlines 
in the 1981 whiskey on the rocks incident a soviet 
whiskeyclass u137 submarine ran aground near the karlskrona naval 
complex moscow termed it an accident and after a confrontation 
that lasted 10 days the sub was released 
in 1982 multiple submarines were identified deep within the 
inner waters of harsfjarden near swedens largest naval base 
covert onshore activity also has targeted the swedish defense 
establishment 
the report cites a 1986 incident in which soviet intelligence 
agents posing as polish art dealers visited the homes of 120 
swedish pilots apparently to determine their identities according 
to swedish authorities it was part of a plan to decimate the royal 
air force in the event of war by gunning down the pilots in their 
homes 
the report said the greater frequency of submarine operations in 
sweden can be linked to soviet suspicion of its status as a neutral 
nation and the increasing strategic value of the scandinavian 
peninsula in soviet contingency war plans 
those plans apparently would involve crossing sweden to reach 
norway which is a nato member the report said 
