<TEXT>
the fading angular script spills across 
a brittle page of the leatherbound courthouse docket seemingly a 
mundane entry in an obscure chapter of frontier justice 
but it is signed lincoln 
the signature makes the 138yearold notation a small piece in 
the historical mosaic being assembled by researchers tracing the 
law career of abraham lincoln who was born 181 years ago today 
without exaggeration its fair to say that this is the last 
real gap in documenting the life of lincoln said cullom davis 
director of the illinois historic preservation agencys lincoln 
legal papers project 
historians are always uncovering new documents of lincoln but 
not very many whats different about this project is that nothing 
has been systematically unearthed and published about his law 
practice thats all theres left to do as far as documenting 
lincoln 
lincoln practiced law from 1837 when the 28yearold 
selfeducated attorney arrived in the muddy frontier town of 
springfield until 1861 then he turned his law practice over to 
his partner of 16 years william herndon and boarded a train for 
washington the white house and the civil war 
in 24 years as a lawyer he handled disputes about stolen hogs 
and bad debts complex appellate cases for railroads and cases 
involving the corporate giants of the frontier he took more than 
260 cases before the illinois supreme court where his was among 
the dominant practices of the time and gained a reputation as a 
writer of forceful succinct briefs 
yet among the approximately 10000 books on lincoln few have 
given thorough accurate treatment to his legal career davis said 
popular accounts portray a humble horseandbuggy lawyer 
dispensing homespun wisdom as he rode from courthouse to 
courthouse a modern legal scholar william prosser dismissed 
lincolns practice as rather petty and uninspiring 
the lincoln legal papers project begun in 1985 and expected to 
take a decade or more seeks to assemble a copy of every obtainable 
document from cases involving lincoln an estimated 70000 papers 
the complete record will be published on microfilm for sale to 
libraries 
but assembling that record is a daunting task 
davis estimates that lincoln handled up to 3000 cases but 
fewer than 400 have been documented the paper chase is complicated 
by the brisk trade in lincoln documents since his 1865 
assassination 
lawyers have them hanging on their walls they exist in 
obscure little libraries that somehow came to own them manuscript 
dealers trade in these things all the time davis said 
persuading the owners of such documents to come forward is often 
difficult davis said because many were originally stolen from 
court files or law firms even lincolns law partner systematically 
filched documents from illinois courthouses after lincolns 
assassination though his plunder is now in the library of congress 
much of the new information about lincolns legal career almost 
certainly will be assembled by combing the files of the illinois 
county courthouses where he practiced 
the tedious search began earlier this month in the menard county 
courthouse at petersburg about 20 miles northwest of springfield 
equipped with a portable photocopier and a computerized index of 
lincolns known cases two researchers are scrutinizing virtually 
every court case from the lincoln era 
menard county is expected to be a particularly rich source 
because it includes the site of new salem the village where 
lincoln once lived the area was home to many of his friends and 
acquaintances 
when my boss asks me how long ill be here i just shrug 
said joanne wallroth a yaletrained documentary editor who 
identified 20 previously unknown lincoln cases in her first week at 
the courthouse 
a typical case from the period finds lincoln representing mentor 
graham new salems schoolteacher in a lawsuit seeking repayment 
of a debt of 1583 from one jacob bale the case dragged on for 
two years before lincoln won a judgment for his client and a fee of 
1990 for himself 
as lincolns practice grew more sophisticated so did the legal 
system because of that parallel davis said the research will 
give historians an insight on the development of the american legal 
system 
the study also is expected to uncover the ways that lincolns 
parallel careers as lawyer and politician shaped one another 
if lincoln hadnt won the presidency in 1860 and had finished 
out his life as a practicing attorney he probably would have 
gone down as one of the great practitioners of the bar in the 
mid19th century davis said 
but thats nothing compared to what he in fact became 
</TEXT>
