<TEXT>
in eight short weeks the new 
leadership in czechoslovakia has done more to establish new ties 
abroad than its communist predecessors did in decades 
under the guidance of former dissidents president vaclav havel 
and foreign minister jiri dienstbier officials are working on 
havels declared goal of restoring czechoslovakias status as the 
spiritual crossroads of europe 
like much of czechoslovakias revolution the process appears 
almost effortless as if planned years in advance 
dienstbier dressed in an unaccustomed suit shakes hands almost 
daily with another foreign minister he apologetically told a 
western reporter this week that march would be the best time for an 
interview hell be away in paris ottawa washington moscow and 
copenhagen until then 
rita klimova known as the voice of the revolution for her 
translation at opposition press conferences in november is off to 
washington as new ambassador 
despite being unable to travel for 20 years these people 
maintained contact in the hard times with eastern european 
dissidents or western intellectuals journalists and politicians 
in this country abounding in ironies the dissidents were better 
informed about thought abroad than other czechoslovaks 
when revolution propelled them to power it was natural that 
their friends abroad would flock to show good will toward the new 
czechoslovakia and perhaps invest in what many western business 
executives see as a coming boom in central europe 
the business and celebrity visitors ranging from british 
playwright harold pinter to american rock star frank zappa are the 
eyecatching part of the serious diplomatic business of putting 
czechoslovakia back on the world map 
havel made his first presidential visit not to moscow like his 
communist predecessors but to east berlin and munich lending 
qualified support to german unification and trying to bury the 
ghost of 1938 the munich agreement that paved the way for hitlers 
invasion of czechoslovakia 
on his first weekend in office dienstbier joined foreign 
minister alois mock of austria in cutting iron curtain barbed wire 
on their border and repeated the same liberating act with foreign 
minister hansdietrich genscher of west germany days later 
last week james a baker iii became the first us secretary of 
state to visit prague since 1973 
it gave us credibility which we really need said karel 
tucek an adviser of the civic forum opposition that powered the 
revolution 
tucek especially liked bakers stress on getting the economy out 
of state hands after two months we have so many businessmen and 
investors trying to find out what they can do but we have to wait 
for parliament to pass the laws 
baker left and foreign minister moshe arens of israel arrived 
to reestablish the diplomatic relations czechoslovakia severed in 
1967 following moscows lead 
there were never so many visits in the last years as in these 
weeks czechoslovakia is again an interesting country dienstbier 
told arens with the understated humor of many of todays prague 
officials 
prague also swiftly followed hungary in establishing ties with 
south korea and emulated poland and hungary in pursuing relations 
with the vatican inviting pope john paul ii in april 
in the reshaping of eastern europe into independent nations 
acting in their own interest prague has already surged ahead of 
its neighbors benefiting perhaps from being later with its revolt 
against the old stalinist ways 
it was the strident demand from prague for the withdrawal of 
soviet troops this year that encouraged hungary and polish 
solidarity leader lech walesa to demand the same 
at last months summit of the ailing sovietled trading bloc 
comecon it was finance minister vaclav klaus who gained attention 
with his threat later modified to quit the organization unless it 
changes radically 
havel journeyed to poland and hungary to propose that the three 
countries meet to coordinate their reentry into europe 
in this effort to change relations with the east havel travels 
to moscow this month the czechoslovak leaders can draw on old 
ties with friends in poland and hungary 
all share the philosophy that powered their dissent the 
creation of a society in which each individual takes responsibility 
for his or her actions 
the effort outlined in havels new year address to bring a 
new element into european and world politics by radiating love 
and understanding also has czechoslovakia looking in less 
conventional directions than simply cultivating the west 
prague wants nato and the warsaw pact to disappear havel has 
offered to mediate between the palestine liberation organization 
the communists mideast friend and israel 
putting personal philosophy ahead of offending china he 
meditated with the tibetan spiritual leader the dalai lama and he 
insisted on squeezing a visit to iceland into his route to the 
white house this month 
there also is a refreshing informality to the efforts to restore 
czechoslovakias standing and infuse new life into world diplomacy 
welcoming arens dienstbier broke protocol and invited him to an 
art exhibit by a man who was his cellmate during a prison term 
why were you in prison arens politely inquired undermining 
of the republic answered dienstbier chuckling 
</TEXT>
