<TEXT>
its jan 18 2006 sarah a 77yearold widow 
living with her son in wheeling wva wakes up as a bedside video 
screen plays sequences of classical music 
she uses her videophone to activate the kitchen coffee maker 
from her bed for her son and then switches the music to his 
bedside screen and turns on a morning news show when her son 
leaves for work she goes back to watching the news which has been 
on hold since she left it 
she dons a medical bracelet and plugs it into the videophone for 
a postoperative checkup from her heart surgery 
later according to a futurist scenario envisioned by the bell 
atlantic telephone company she leaves an audiovideo message for a 
friend listens to a talking book club and when she goes to 
bed programs an emergency pager that will if need be track down 
her son by phone 
bell atlantic says the whizbang gadgets sarah will take for 
granted are technically feasible now and could be in the average 
americans home by the end of the century 
but first bell atlantic and the other regional bell companies 
say theyve got to get the government off their backs 
rep edward markey dmass took a step in that direction 
friday when he unveiled a bill to loosen the restrictions on 
information services and equipment manufacturing placed on the bell 
companies in the 1984 consent decree that broke up the american 
telephone amp telegraph co 
previous efforts to free the bells have gone nowhere in 
congress opponents fear that unrestrained bell companies could use 
their enormous resources to drive out competition by limiting phone 
access and by crosssubsidizing their new and riskier business 
ventures with their heavy local telephone earnings 
but markey whose bill joins a similar measure introduced by 
sen ernest hollings dsc says it is time to defend us 
telecommunications leadership against intense foreign competition 
markeys bill would give the federal communications commission 
the oversight powers held by us district judge harold greene who 
continues to enforce the 1984 consent decree 
greene in 1986 gave the bells permission to transmit information 
services such as videotext computer data bases financial 
information and reservation and shopping services but would not 
allow them to control the content of such services 
markeys bill would allow the bell companies among other 
things to provide through nonjoint venture subsidiaries 
distribution of information services outside their calling 
territories 
electronic yellow pages directories excluding classified 
advertising to be updated monthly for two years 
emergency public safety services such as enhanced 911 calling 
research design and development of telecommunications 
equipment and under certain conditions equipment manufacturing 
the bill contains mechanisms designed to prevent crosssubsidies 
and other anticompetitive practices but allows the fcc to waive 
the separate subsidiary requirement after three years the 
information service restrictions do not apply when a bell company 
owns 5 percent or less of an information services company 
initial reaction from the bell companies to the bill was 
cautiously optimistic bellsouth described it as another 
significant step toward bringing america up to speed in 
telecommunications while bell atlantic said it was another 
clear signal that congress recognizes the need to address 
telecommunications policy for the nation 
however gene kimmelman legislative director of the consumer 
federation of america was hesitant 
this is a valiant effort to limit ratepayer risks but it is 
not clear that the bill provides more concrete consumer benefits 
than current law were still skeptical of the need for this kind 
of legislation kimmelman said 
mci communications corp said the bill was unneeded and will 
set back americas preeminence and global leadership in 
telecommunications 
although the consent decree didnt specifically mention cable 
television in the information services ban court interpretations 
have included cable in that ban 
owning cable tv service is crucial to the bells plan to wire 
the nation with fiberoptic cable that could make a sarah 
household a reality but the cable industry is adamant about 
keeping the phone companies out of their business and the markey 
bill does not change the cable tv curbs 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

