<TEXT>
here is a brief chronology of 
south africas recent political history 
1912 the south african native national congress forerunner of 
the african national congress is formed to fight for black 
political rights 
1948 the national party government is elected and begins 
codifying apartheid legislation 
1955 a national peoples congress is broken up and 156 black 
leaders including nelson mandela are charged with treason all 
are acquitted after a trial that lasts until 1961 
march 21 1960 the anc and the pan africanist congress call 
for peaceful protests against laws requiring blacks to have passses 
to enter white areas police shoot and kill 69 blacks at a rally in 
the sharpeville township south of johannesburg 
april 1960 parliament outlaws the anc and the pac both 
organizations launch guerrilla campaigns a year later 
aug 5 1962 mandela is arrested and two years later is 
sentenced to life in prison for sabotage and plotting to overthrow 
the government 
june 16 1976 thousands of black students demonstrate in the 
soweto township outside johannesburg protesting a requirement that 
lessons be taught in the afrikaans language police fatally shoot 
several students touching off nationwide riots and boycotts that 
last more than a year and claim at least 575 black lives 
sept 12 1977 steve biko founder of the black consciousness 
movement dies in police detention 
oct 19 1977 the government bans 18 organizations and the two 
largest black newspapers it also detains 47 black leaders 
aug 20 1983 the united democratic front is launched to 
organize opposition to a planned threehouse parliament that still 
excludes blacks the front quickly becomes the largest legal 
antiapartheid group 
september 1983 riots break out in sharpeville touching off 
three years of widespread violence claiming at least 2500 black 
lives 
june 12 1986 president pw botha declares a nationwide state 
of emergency giving authorities broad powers to crack down on 
opposition groups more than 1000 activists are detained in 
predawn raids more than 30000 people almost all black have 
been held for varying lengths of time during the emergency 
feb 24 1988 the government effectively bans 17 opposition 
groups including the united democratic front 
july 5 1989 botha invites the jailed mandela to the 
presidents office for a conversation 
aug 14 1989 botha resigns and is replaced by fw de klerk 
september 1989 de klerk says he will allow peaceful 
antigovernment protest demonstrations in all major cities are 
held without serious incident 
oct 15 1989 de klerk frees six of mandelas anc colleagues 
imprisoned for more than 25 years including walter sisulu 
dec 13 1989 de klerk meets mandela at the presidents office 
feb 2 de klerk legalizes the anc and dozens of other banned 
opposition groups and says mandela soon will be freed 
unconditionally 
saturday de klerk announces that mandela will be released 
unconditionally the next day 
sunday mandela leaves prison 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

