<TEXT>
scientists who have spent the past 
decade assessing the impact of acid rain on the nation will share 
their results this week with their counterparts from around the 
globe 
the national acidic rain assessment program a consortium of 11 
federal agencies was established 10 years ago by congress and has 
spent 500 million investigating the problem 
it is holding a conference on hilton head island to review data 
from the studies 
one conclusion likely to provoke controversy at the conference 
is that acid rain generally isnt harming the nations forests 
said joseph barnard a us forest service researcher who headed 
the work of forest scientists the charlotte nc observer said 
in saturday editions 
the newspaper said it obtained a report expected to be presented 
at the conference intended to summarize various scientific studies 
of acid rain the report says that ozone does far more damage to 
trees than acid rain although acid rain may be harming red spruces 
in the appalachians northward to new england 
the world resources institute a washingtonbased environmental 
group disputes the findings saying evidence is unambiguous 
that acid rain and ozone both contribute to the deaths of trees in 
the south east and west 
according to the newspaper the report also says that a national 
survey found that only 4 percent of the nations lakes and 6 
percent of the streams were acidic 
researcher lawrence baker of the university of minnesota said 
that eventually the soils will be unable to neutralize any more 
acid the question is 10 50 100 years baker said theres 
quite a bit of debate on that 
acid rain is a combination of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide 
that mixes in the atmosphere and can be carried hundreds of miles 
before falling back to earth as rain snow fog and dust particles 
affecting aquatic life trees and humans 
much of the pollution comes from power plants which burn high 
sulphur coal although other industrial facilities also generate the 
pollutants 
about 1000 researchers have been at work during the past decade 
compiling 28 draft studies on the impact of acid rain 
the whole purpose is to give outsiders a chance to critique 
the reports its a chance to get them out into the broader 
scientific community said chuck herrick a spokesman for the 
agency who said the review is probably the most comprehensive ever 
compiled 
later information from the technical reports will be integrated 
into a final document the computer models will be used to map 
various emission control strategies 
herrick said we will be running 30 scenarios for the future 
the assumption then is the policy people will be looking at this 
and will be able to make their decisions 
the agency itself is not mandated to make policy decisions 
simply provide policymakers with the best data possible he added 
president bush unveiled his clean air bill last year a measure 
that would sharply reduce urban smog toxic chemical air pollution 
and acid rain by the end of the decade 
bush has called for a 10 million ton reduction in sulfur dioxide 
one of the main ingredients in acid rain by the turn of the 
century 
while the administration unveiled its legislation before the 
agency assessments were released i dont know that the 
conclusion is that the administration bill is wholly lacking in 
scientific basis herrick said 
our people were extensively contacted the argument could be 
made the bill does have a scientific basis he added 
he said 600 scientists from 35 nations are attending the 
conference which opened sunday and continues through friday 
