harold mccusker a 
schoolteacher who became prominent in northern ireland politics 
died in a hospital monday after a 16year battle with cancer his 
family announced he was 50 
mccusker was a member of the british parliament for 16 years 
representing the official unionists the mainstream protestant 
party in northern ireland he was party deputy leader from 1982 
the diminutive bespectacled politician was an eloquent speaker 
and campaigner for tougher measures against the irish republican 
army which is fighting to rid northern ireland of british rule 
like most northern ireland protestants mccusker fervently 
opposed the 1985 angloirish agreement that gave the irish republic 
a say in running the province 
he served a fourday jail sentence in january 1987 for not 
paying the annual 75 car tax in protest of the accord 
but he later became critical of older colleagues for failing to 
come up with an alternative to the angloirish pact and 
coauthored an end to drift an influential analysis of ways 
out of the impasse 
mccusker is survived by his wife jennifer and sons moore 
james and colin 
