<TEXT>
until three years ago a state legislator 
from the appalachian hills of eastern kentucky says he never gave 
much thought to aids assuming his family and friends were immune 
from a disease that he considered a bigcity problem 
state rep paul masons sense of security ended abruptly when 
his daughter belinda mason contracted the aids virus through a 
blood transfusion in 1987 
his daughters plight spurred the used car salesman from 
whitesburg to action putting him on the front lines of a fight to 
promote aids education prevent discrimination and curb the spread 
of the disease 
it really wasnt a part of my world mason said youre 
sitting in middle class america and aids is just not a part of your 
world now its something i live with every waking moment 
after learning of his daughters affliction mason said his 
apathy turned to anger he was bitter at the blood donor and health 
care officials 
you want to go after somebody with your bare hands mason 
said im not sure ill ever be able to look at my daughter 
and forgive him blood donor nobody has a right to steal part of 
me 
but mason has learned to channel his emotions in another 
direction the 1988 general assembly enacted his bill to make it 
illegal to use blood for transfusions before the blood is tested 
for aids contamination 
this year mason introduced sweeping aids legislation to foster 
a greater understanding of aids and to wipe out discrimination 
when she contracted it there was a world of discrimination out 
there and a lot in the health care field because everyone was 
scared he said in the health care field i have seen a world 
of change in attitude 
mason removed the proposals two most controversial sections 
one would have allowed a murder charge to be brought against a 
person who knowingly gives an uninformed sexual partner aids 
resulting in the partners death the second would have allowed the 
state cabinet for human resources to obtain court orders to detain 
people infected with sexually transmitted diseases in hospitals 
the bill still would require extensive education programs for 
state and local agencies and mandatory aids training for health 
professionals it also would give aids patients the same legal 
protections as handicapped people 
ms mason 31 who was appointed by president bush last year to 
the national commission on aids said her fathers bill symbolizes 
the type of government action needed to assist aids patients 
we have to stop relying on peoples good manners and have some 
solid legal guidelines on how to treat people infected with the 
aids virus she said 
mason said his bill stems from watching his daughter who lives 
in hartford ky fight discrimination 
ms mason said much of her fathers bill came two years too 
late for me but is intended to protect other aids patients from 
encountering the same hostility and hardships 
what my dad has attempted to do is to make the road for people 
who come after me easier said ms mason who found out in 
october that her infection has developed into aids 
he wasnt doing it just for his child but for the countless 
others who have contracted the disease she said 
ms mason said people suffering from the disease are engaged in 
the same fight as blacks women and other minority groups in 
seeking to end discrimination 
she is treated well when she visits home in letcher county in 
the heart of appalachia her father said but other aids victims 
have encountered discrimination there he said 
one letcher county man who is fighting aids has concealed his 
ailment from friends and neighbors telling them hes suffering 
from another disease because he fears being ostracized mason said 
that kind of points up the need for education and 
dissemination of information he said 
