<TEXT>
issues ranging from rudder control designs to 
the effects of airline mergers on safety are expected to come up in 
a hearing opening tuesday into last falls crash in new york of 
usair flight 5050 
national transportation safety board chairman james l kolstad 
who will conduct the fourday hearing in new york said 
crewmembers airline officials federal aviation administration 
experts and representatives of the boeing co are expected to 
testify 
two people were killed and 61 others were saved in a massive 
rescue operation after the boeing 737 airliner skidded off the end 
of a laguardia airport runway and into the east river breaking 
into pieces in an aborted takeoff 
the crash has raised several safety issues and drawn attention 
to more than a dozen reports of problems with rudder controls on 
boeing 737s 
kolstad said in a recent interview that the engineering and 
mechancial design of the rudder trim on boeing 737s will be among 
issues taken up at the hearing investigators found that flight 
5050s rudder was improperly trimmed to full left although cockpit 
recorders indicated pilots had properly checked the rudders 
position for takeoff 
pilot michael martin reported the plane was drifting to the left 
before he aborted the takeoff which was being handled by copilot 
constantine kleissas 
the plane was scheduled to fly to charlotte nc 
we feel the rudder trim system is what actually precipitated 
the usair accident air line pilots association representative 
tom kraemer said monday the pilots union and other interested 
groups will participate in the hearing 
other matters to be explored during the hearing include cockpit 
crew training and crew coordination by usair its flight operations 
and the recent merger of usair with piedmont and its impact on 
flight operations kolstad said 
the planes copilot came to usair in the merger kleissas was 
controlling takeoff of a 737 for the first time since training for 
the airliner 
the safety board chairman said the hearing also will cover faa 
surveillance of usair operations and runway design including 
whether it is advisable to install arresting gear at the ends of 
