<TEXT>
top us and soviet trade officials began 
negotiations monday aimed at wiping away nearly a halfcentury of 
trade frictions between the two superpowers by the time of the 
bushgorbachev summit in june 
both sides expressed optimism that a new trade treaty could be 
completed by then even though the complexity of the talks was 
highlighted by the size of the delegations and the length of the 
negotiating agenda 
the us team led by trade representative carla hills and her 
deputy julius l katz included 19 officials from six agencies 
including the departments of state treasury commerce and labor 
the first round of negotiations which were scheduled to last 
through tuesday were to be followed by two more sessions in late 
february and early march the monday session included morning and 
afternoon meetings separated by a working lunch 
us officials said they hoped that all of the negotiations 
would be completed by the end of april to provide time to draft the 
final trade agreement so that it can be signed by president bush 
and soviet president mikhail gorbachev at their june meeting in 
washington 
as the talks got under way hills told reporters that she was 
confident that the differences separating the two sides could be 
ironed out noting her soviet counterparts she said we are a 
very efficient team 
yuriy n chumakov deputy minister of foreign economic affairs 
and the leader of the soviet delegation urged reporters to hold 
their questions about the chances for success until negotiators had 
finished the initial round of talks 
hills listed as goals normalizing trade relations with the 
soviet union and facilitating trade between the two countries 
the administration hopes that normalized trade will give a boost 
to the soviet economy and provide economic support to the political 
reforms being undertaken by gorbachev 
the trade treaty would be used to grant the soviet union most 
favored nation status qualifying it for the lowest tariffs 
granted to any other country 
the soviets are anxious to obtain this benefit since their 
imports to the united states must currently bear duties as much as 
10 times higher than imports from other nations 
the higher tariffs are a result of a 1974 law known as the 
jacksonvanik amendment which was passed by congress in 
retaliation for the refusal of the soviet government to allow 
soviet jews and other dissidents to leave the country 
bush has said he will ask congress to waive the jacksonvanik 
restrictions once the soviet legislature passes a law spelling out 
its new liberalized emigration policies the new trade treaty would 
be needed to put the lower tariffs into effect 
hungary recently obtained a waiver from the high jacksonvanik 
tariffs in addition to the soviet union the administration is 
also considering granting waivers for czechoslovakia romania 
bulgaria and east germany the curbs against poland were lifted in 
1987 
one of the issues in the soviet negotiations will be how the 
waiver from the high tariffs will be accomplished the 
administration would like to negotiate a threeyear trade agreement 
with annual presidential review and waiver of the high tariffs 
the soviets would like to see the tariffs removed permanently as 
a way of building confidence among business leaders that trade 
relations will remain stable in coming years 
but congress which is following the present negotiations with 
keen interest is unlikely to go along with more than a oneyear 
waiver 
other issues on the opening agenda were us demands for 
protection of americanpatented products from piracy an 
arbitration method to settle business disputes and provisions to 
allow either country to impose temporary trade restrictions if a 
domestic industry suffers injury because of an unexpected surge of 
imports 
the administration is predicting that twoway trade between the 
two countries could double or even triple over the next three years 
with a new trade agreement although private economists doubt that 
assessment given the numerous troubles plaguing the soviet economy 
through november the united states had sold 382 billion worth 
of exports to the soviets primarily farm products while importing 
a relatively small 658 million worth of soviet products primarily 
oil platinum and consumer goods such as vodka and furs 
trade relations between the united states and the soviet union 
began deteriorating with the onset of cold war tensions following 
world war ii in 1947 president truman placed restrictions on us 
exports to the soviet union in an effort to keep militaryuseful 
technologies from falling into communist hands 
</TEXT>
