the ford foundation invited 200 colleges and 
universities on monday to compete for 16 million in grants aimed 
at improving race relations and exploring other cultures 
we are looking for projects that will help weave diversity 
into the fabric of an institutions academic life and sense of 
purpose ford foundation president franklin a thomas said in a 
news release 
the grants are being made because thomas said in a letter sent 
to education leaders on many college campuses reports of racial 
and religious intolerance and sexual harassment are rising 
diversity makes an essential contribution to the education of 
students thomas wrote but added that some students find 
diversity confusing or threatening 
for these students college is often the first journey out of 
a homogeneous neighborhood into a more diverse world those who are 
not ready or willing to relate to people of a different race 
religion or sexual orientation or to relate to people with 
profoundly different political and ethical convictions will be 
troubled and may express this through disruptive and hostile 
behavior 
the grants may be used for course development or revision study 
groups colloquia cultural affairs visiting speakers and for 
acquiring or preserving materials used in undergraduate courses 
the foundation plans to award 10 grants of up to 100000 each 
for new programs and smaller grants of up to 25000 to expand or 
enhance existing programs 
those asked to participate are schools that are largely or 
wholly residential they include small schools like berea college 
in kentucky and lincoln university in pennsylvania and larger 
universities and colleges like yale in connecticut and the 
university of california 
the ford foundation established in 1936 is a private 
nonprofit institution whose goal is to preserve peace and advance 
human welfare the foundation headquartered in new york has 
granted 7 billion to more than 9000 institutions and 100000 
individuals worldwide 
