<TEXT>
a special state environmental panel on monday 
called for increased public disclosure about operations at the 
rocky flats nuclear weapons plant 
in order to be a responsible neighbor to millions of people 
living nearby the rocky flats plant must be open and honest about 
its operations and their impact and be willing to listen and 
respond to the communitys concerns said state rep sam 
williams chairman of the rocky flats environmental monitoring 
council 
gov roy romer and us rep david skaggs appointed the 
11member council in january 1988 to promote communication between 
the plant and concerned public agencies and the public and to 
monitor environmental safety and public health concerns 
the plant 16 miles northwest of denver manufactures highly 
radioactive plutonium detonators for nuclear weapons 
it has been under investigation by a federal grand jury since 
shortly after a raid on june 6 1989 by scores of fbi and 
environmental protection agency agents investigating allegations of 
illegal radioactive waste storage and disposal 
plutonium operations at the plant were suspended in november by 
energy secretary james watkins until health and safety concerns are 
met no startup date has been announced but sources have said 
plutonium processing could resume in late spring or summer 
the doe also transferred management of the plant to egampg a 
major defense contractor from rockwell international on jan 1 
the council noted in its report that improved communication is 
critically needed doe and its contractors have historically 
demonstrated a reluctance to share information about the general 
operation of rocky flats about incidents and problems that have 
occurred and about anticipated future problems this lack of 
openness has aggravated public mistrust of the plant and its 
possible impacts upon the environment and public health safety 
melinda kassen a senior attorney for the environmental defense 
fund said the report contains nothing new or revolutionary 
the report serves as an exclamation point at the end of whats 
already been said kassen added 
kassen said the bush administration did not include funding in 
its budget proposal for the plants fiveyear plan for 
environmental restoration new initiatives for waste management and 
corrective activities for complying with existing legal 
requirements 
among the reports recommendations 
full funding of health studies to assess the effect of plant 
discharges on the community and reactivation and expansion of a 
study of effects on rocky flats workers 
minimum level plutonium processing until a previously initiated 
safety review is completed and all suggested corrective actions are 
implemented 
strict air emission monitoring 
issuance of publicinformation papers by the rocky flats plant 
openly discussing tough issues facing the plant 
placement of various oversight responsibilities for nuclear 
weapons plants outside the department of energy 
formal agreement not to permanently dispose of any wastes at 
rocky flats and to put a premium on eliminating offsite discharges 
of hazardous materials 
</TEXT>
