<TEXT>
the massive landidling conservation reserve 
program will boost farm income and improve environmental quality 
through the end of the century an agriculture department report 
said monday 
but consumers will pay somewhat higher food prices as farmers 
take up to 45 million acres of highly erodible cropland from 
production under 10year contracts the report said 
the crp was authorized by the 1985 farm law and signups so far 
have resulted in about 34 million acres an area almost the size of 
michigan 
consumer food costs will climb by 127 billion to 252 
billion over the life of the crp peaking around 1995 the report 
said food cost increases will be less than 1 percent in any 
given year 
under the plan farmers agree to take fragile highly erodible 
land from crop production and plant it to protective grass and 
trees 
in return the government helps pay the cost of the initial 
plantings and then pays the farmer annual rent during the 10 years 
of the contract the payments average about 50 per acre annually 
the report prepared by the departments economic research 
service was based on an assumption that the maximum of 45 million 
acres would be enrolled in the longterm program 
however congress set a minimum of 40 million acres to go with 
the maximum of 45 million acres and administration officials have 
indicated the minimum will be the target 
robert j gray a private conservation specialist and 
consultant said 45 million acres had been thought a reasonable 
goal for the crp he said 5 million acres probably could be added 
to the minimum 40 million through tree plantings in shelterbelts 
windbreaks and other projects 
i would prefer 45 million acres no question about it gray 
said in a telephone interview he said he had not seen the new usda 
report 
the report said that 45 million acres in the crp for 10 years 
increases commodity prices and reduces environmental problems 
linked with soil erosion 
further it added the price increases and production cuts 
cause ripple effects in the farm sector agricultural industries 
and other segments of the economy related to us agriculture 
farm income based on present values will rise by 92 
billion to 203 billion between 1986 and 1999 from higher 
commodity prices and lower production costs the report said 
landowners who plant trees as the cover crop on approximately 35 
million crp acres will gain 41 billion to 54 billion in 
wealth 
environmental benefits were estimated at 6 billion to 136 
billion mostly in offfarm areas being affected by agricultural 
soil erosion the value of improvements in surface water quality 
from the crp ranges from 19 billion to 53 billion 
wildlife habitat improvement was valued from 3 billion to 47 
billion and wind erosion abatement was projected at 400 million 
to 11 billion 
a 45millionacre crp will cost the federal government 215 
billion to 228 billion in rents bonuses costsharing and 
technical assistance the report said most of these costs are 
offset by savings in price and income support payments to farmers 
</TEXT>
