<TEXT>
a congressional international affairs expert 
on monday described president bushs andean drug initiative as a 
major turning point in us drug policy but a specialist in 
the region said the policy is doomed to failure unless attention is 
paid to the needs of cocagrowing peasants 
raphael francis perl a specialist in international affairs with 
the congressional research service of the library of congress said 
the bush initiative calling for 22 billion in aid to countries 
in the region over five years represents an increased awareness 
of the economic and trade component of drug policy 
kevin healy interamerican foundation representative for 
bolivia and ecuador on the other hand said we have had 
economic aid and cropsubstitution programs going on in bolivia 
since 1976 if they are implemented with the same kind of 
understanding of the peasant economy and the national agricultural 
problems i think they are doomed to fail 
i think we have got to go in and get serious about not 
economic development but peasant economic development putting the 
emphasis there we have had economic development before but it 
seldom gets through to the peasantry im sort of a disbeliever 
until i can see that its not just business as usual in foreign 
aid 
perl and healy spoke at a briefing called by the panos institute 
in connection with this weeks drug summit in cartagena colombia 
the organization founded in 1986 primarily by environmental 
journalists describes itself as an independent international 
institute working for sustainable development its sources of 
funds include the governments of denmark finland the netherlands 
norway sweden and britain as well as international organizations 
and the ford and rockefeller foundations 
a study distributed at the briefing said no approach to the drug 
crisis is likely to succeed unless it deals with the problems of 
farmers who grow the coca leaves from which cocaine is made 
the study by patricia ardila a colombian magazine journalist 
who is director of the institutes narcotics and development 
information program said cocaine money plays a vital role in 
helping to cushion the economic crisis facing bolivia and peru due 
to debt and structural adjustment and in contributing to 
colombias healthier economic performance 
at the same time the study said traditional or new elites 
are amassing immense fortunes through cocaine trafficking and 
helping to reinforce the inequalities that have prevailed in 
these countries for centuries 
the illegal nature of these economic activities which makes 
violence the chief means used by traffickers to regulate the 
cocaine business combined with the international response to the 
drug trade which has overlooked the issues of poverty and 
underdevelopment facing coca producers is occurring at enormous 
cost to the andean countries ms ardila said 
whatever solutions are proposed chances are that none are 
likely to succeed unless coca producers can participate in all 
stages of the process to ensure that their economic and social 
needs are met she wrote 
perl whose duties include advising members of congress on 
international drug control said there is no question that the 
us invasion of panama has placed significant obstacles to drug 
policy in the short term 
he said that on a recent trip to peru he expected people to ask 
him about drugs but most of the questions he got were about the 
us invasion that resulted in the arrest of panamanian gen manuel 
antonio noriega 
in the long run however perl said he is more hopeful about 
prospects for us drug policy in the region 
i believe that the bush initiative represents a major turning 
point in us international narcotics control policy he said 
