<TEXT>
the bush administration is easing away from a 
proposal that would have required automakers to produce up to a 
million alternate fuel cars as part of tougher air pollution 
controls officials acknowledged monday 
when president bush proposed a broadranging program last summer 
to clean up the nations air the centerpiece of plans to combat 
urban smog was a call for legislation requiring automakers to 
provide up to 1 million new cars annually by 1997 that could run on 
fuels other than gasoline 
the cars would be sold in nine cities where smog is worst and 
were calculated eventually to reach 30 percent of the motor vehicle 
fleets in those areas 
but william reilly head of the environmental protection agency 
confirmed monday that the administration no longer considers 
requiring the production of such cars which would use fuels such 
as methanol or natural gas as essential to curbing urban smog 
instead the administration is proposing in negotiations with 
senate leaders that a form of reformulated gasoline which 
would also reduce smogcausing pollution might be an alternative 
to automobiles using nongasoline fuels 
vehicles using reformulated lowpolluting gasoline do not 
require any additional equipment or modifications atlantic 
richfield co already is selling reformulated gasoline in 
california 
reilly rejected sugestions that the change was a weakening of 
the administration proposal to reduce automobile pollution 
there is no change in the goals or the performance objectives 
that we want to achieve but we have tried to indicate more 
flexibility about methods of getting there he told reporters 
legislation before the senate to tighten federal air pollution 
controls does not include a requirement for alternative fuel 
vehicles and instead would impose new automobile tailpipe 
emission controls that the auto industry has vigorously opposed 
but the white house has opposed the additional tailpipe emission 
requirements arguing that an alternative fuels vehicle program 
focused on the areas with the dirtiest air is more economical and 
achieves nearly as much pollution reduction 
some senate democrats have voiced frustration in recent days 
over the changes in the administrations proposal maintaining that 
while the white house opposes tougher exhaust controls it is also 
weakening the approach it is trying to sell as a substitute 
reilly acknowledged that the administrations original proposal 
requiring automakers to produce and sell a specific number of 
alternative fuel vehicles has caused us considerable opposition 
and kept some senators from joining in support 
we have been willing for some months to redraft some language 
on the alternative fuels proposal to try to reassure people that 
we do not prefer one fuel over another as long as the overall 
pollution reduction is the same said reilly 
reilly suggested for example legislation that would require 
all new cars in a polluted urban area to use the reformulated 
gasoline may accomplish the same pollution reductions as requiring 
30 percent of cars in the area to run on something other than 
gasoline 
