demanding the party withdraw from the workplace and that talks be 
suspended until a consensus is reached 
the state bta news agency said the opposition represented by 
the loosely grouped union of democratic forces renewed its demand 
that communist party organizations in factories and other work 
places be dissolved 
last month the communists announced plans to remove party 
control of the armed forces and police 
on monday the communists agreed that party organizations should 
also be banned from state offices the judiciary education and 
health care but not from the factory floor bta reported 
the opposition wants a constitutional amendment placed before 
parliament to dissolve party organizations at factories before the 
elections set for may 
bta said the opposition also wants action postponed on a measure 
dealing with political parties but the communists also rejected 
this proposal 
on tuesday a working group will meet to try to reach a 
compromise it said 
bta reported that a spokesman for the opposition not 
identified accused the communists of stalling at the talks to 
impede the oppositions election campaign 
the union of democratic forces has been negotiating for more 
powersharing with the communists who have so far rejected demands 
for opposition access to radio and televison that would take their 
platforms nationwide 
according to bta however reform communists who split from the 
party to form an alternative socialist party last sunday backed 
opposition demands as did the oncedocile agrarian party 
the opposition rejected an offer by the agrarian party to seek 
an intermediary role and take part in the talks as a third 
negotiating partner 
zhelyu zhelev chairman of the union of democratic forces 
observed that the agrarians had not gone into opposition according 
to bta zhelev invited the agrarians to join his group 
premier andrei lukanov was forced to form the countrys first 
allcommunist government last week after the agrarian party 
announced it would no longer knuckle under to the communists and 
the opposition refused to heed communist calls to join the 
government 
