<TEXT>
turkey opened sluice gates of the huge 
ataturk dam on monday allowing euphrates river water to flow south 
to syria and iraq 
turkey diverted the rivers main flow jan 13 to increase the 
water level in the ataturk reservoir and finish some construction 
work on diversion channels 
iraq and syria protested that their agricultural land might be 
damaged and their electricity production reduced 
cengiz altinkaya the public works minister said at the dam 
site 60 miles from the syrian border near sanliurfa that the 
diversion channel opened monday was closed in july 1988 and work 
also was done on a second channel closed in may his remarks were 
carried by the semiofficial anatolia news agency 
ataturk dams reservoir has three main diversion channels the 
third was blocked last month and will not be opened for some time 
the agency report said 
during the cutoff period syria and iraq got water from 
downstream tributaries of the euphrates but the flow was reduced 
to about onefifth the usual 500 cubic meters per second altinkaya 
said average flow was being resumed monday 
the euphrates originates in the mountains of eastern turkey and 
flows 1460 miles through syria and iraq to confluence with the 
tigris river and persian gulf 
anatolia quoted officials at the dam as saying about 25 billion 
cubic meters of water had accumulated in the ataturk reservoir 
whose full capacity is nearly 20 times that 
tobacco farmers in western turkey rioted for higher support 
prices monday breaking shop windows blocking highways and 
fighting police news agencies reported 
anatolia said several thousand farmers blocked traffic for about 
four hours by sitting on the railway line that connects akhisar in 
the aegean region to istanbul and on the three major highways that 
run through the town 
hurriyet an independent agency said the farmers later moved 
into the center of akhisar 320 miles southwest of ankara and 
broke the windows of the tobacco shops and the state cigarette 
monopoly building 
the farmers threw stones at police trying to disperse the crowd 
and police arrested an undetermined number hurriyet reported 
support prices are what stateowned cigarette factories will pay 
for the next tobacco crop because cigarette production is a 
virtual government monopoly they also determine the freemarket 
price 
this years support price was set 54 percent higher than for the 
last crop but farmers complain that it falls short of the 65 
percent annual inflation rate 
resit kursun head of turkish chambers of agriculture told 
state radio the price would not enable the farmers to repay their 
production loans 
