<TEXT>
scientists gathered to review a 
10year study on the causes and effects of acid rain were warned 
monday that their work wont provide a quick fix for policymakers 
the full story is seldom if ever known about the complex 
issues of environmental science said william rosenberg an 
assistant administrator for the federal environmental protection 
agency 
scientific investigation must continue including an 
evaluation of the control program put in place rosenberg said 
in the meantime we must take prudent actions to protect our 
health and our environment 
about 700 scientists from across the united states and 35 
foreign countries have gathered to review 28 draft reports on acid 
rain compiled by the national acidic rain assessment program the 
program was established 10 years ago by congress and has spent 500 
million investigating acid rain which is caused by air pollution 
and is said to pose the greatest threat to lakes in the northeast 
and upper midwest 
acid rain is a blanket term for a combination of sulfur dioxide 
and nitrogen oxide which mixes in the atmosphere and can fall as 
rain snow fog or dust particles it can make lakes and streams 
acidic and can kill trees 
along with smog acid rain is a target of clean air legislation 
being considered in congress that would would reduce pollution from 
factories power plants and automobiles 
about 1000 researchers have been at work during the past decade 
compiling the reports being considered at the conference the 
documents dont take policy stands 
you have changed the way the world thinks about acid rain and 
youve helped policymakers decide which steps need to be taken 
said michael deland chairman of the council on environmental 
quality 
but he added it is highly unlikely well reach scientific 
certainty on issues like acid rain 
that thought was echoed by james mahoney director of the 
assessment program 
we must critically analyze all our hypotheses but there is no 
way the scientific community can provide a single answer that this 
is the level for reducing industrial emmissions 
most of the reports which are the focus of the meeting have been 
released over the past two months this weeks meeting gives 
scientists from aboard a chance to review the material 
discussions monday centered on acidity in the nations streams 
and lakes based on sampling completed in the mid1980s 
the survey found that 42 percent of the 1181 lakes sampled 
were considered acidic with the most acidic lakes in the northeast 
the upper midwest and florida 
the study also found that 27 percent of the 5506 kilometers of 
streams sampled are acidic most of those streams in the 
appalachian mountains and the midatlantic coastal plain 
</TEXT>
