aircraft still stand in the way of completing a treaty this year to 
limit nonnuclear forces 
he criticized soviet president mikhail s gorbachev for 
rejecting a proposal by bush that would permit the united states to 
keep 30000 troops in britain italy and spain while both sides 
were held to 195000 in central europe 
gorbachev countered with ceilings of 225000 soviet troops to 
195000 us soldiers on foreign soil throughout europe that 
would in effect prevent a us numerical edge because the soviets 
could offset in central europe any americans stationed eslewhere on 
the continent 
bush monday said he stood by his plan 
baker said gorbachevs proposal for equal ceilings had not taken 
into account that the soviets could quickly expand their forces in 
a crisis while american troops would be an ocean away 
baker also criticized the soviets resistance to imposing 
ceilings on aircraft that moscow claims have a defensive role this 
was hardly a step toward arms reduction baker said 
raising the prospect of an impasse baker said disagreements 
over aircraft limits must not prevent us from signing a cfe 
conventional forces in europe agreement this year 
a senior us official suggested however that the issue might 
be finessed by leaving airplanes out of the treaty 
bakers tough approach seemed in contrast with his description 
in moscow last friday of gorbachevs proposal on troop levels as 
very very interesting and close to bushs approach he said 
he would consult the nato allies before giving a us reply 
a response and an early agreement now appears to be unlikely 
before baker flies home tuesday night 
baker and shevardnadze met outside the conference to discuss 
german reunification they set another meeting for tuesday 
baker suggested this scenario according to state department 
officials 
after east germany holds elections march 18 officials of the 
new government would meet with west german leaders to begin 
planning unification 
they would make decisions on the new germanys legal and 
political arrangements and the size of its army 
afterward the united states the soviet union britain and 
france would discuss security arrangements to allay the 
concerns of germanys neighbors 
as sovereign states however the two germanys would have 
control of the nations destiny 
the soviets have stressed those concerns and shevardnadze 
proposed two weeks ago an international plebisicite 
but the state department officials who spoke on condition of 
anonymity said the soviets were quite interested in the us 
proposal and that it had the endorsement of britain and france 
