<TEXT>
angry black students carrying the banner 
keep the dream alive marched out of selma high school on 
monday ending a fiveday sitin but decided they wouldnt return 
to class when the school reopens 
in another development a federal judge turned down the citys 
request to halt a sitin at city hall in this landmark city of the 
civil rights era 
mayor joe smitherman announced that all schools would reopen 
tuesday but the racial protest that brought public education to a 
halt last week seemed far from resolved some white parents said 
they were transferring children to other school systems 
superintendent norward roussell whose dismissal at the end the 
school year sparked the protests ordered teachers to report at 
715 am tuesday and predicted that about 70 percent of the school 
systems 6000 students would be in class 
i anticipate some of our students will not show up tomorrow 
but we will have students tomorrow and we will have regular classes 
for those students roussell said monday 
more than 100 black students who took part in the sitin voted 
monday night to march to the high school when it reopened tuesday 
but said they wouldnt attend classes 
the students met in the basement of first baptist church while 
more than 300 adults sat upstairs singing hymns 
after the vote roussell told the parents and students it was 
their decision how to react to schools reopening but added i 
didnt come here to be superintendent over empty classrooms and 
closed schools 
us district judge charles butler of mobile after hearing 
arguments partly through a telephone hookup refused earlier in the 
