<TEXT>
each citys style became subtly distinctive an aid for future 
antiquarians since few pieces in the chippendale era were signed 
it was an anonymous business presumably because everybody knew who 
made what ballandclaw feet were squared off at the bottom in new 
york carved with pronounced knuckles in philadelphia without 
webbing between the talons in newport 
the townsends and goddards became known for their blockfront 
furniture convex panels surrounding a third concave panel and 
topped with a carved scallop shell a common adornment along with 
stars and radiating suns it was a style that came to newport from 
italy by way of boston 
customarily several crafts contributed to a block front 
deskbookcase the lathe turner the brass hardware maker 
sometimes the carver they would turn over their pieces to the 
cabinetmaker who put them all together and got credit for the 
final product so it was presumably with john goddards 121 
million blockfront desk although he probably did the carving 
himself 
actually no one is positive goddard made the desk it is 
unsigned its a reasonably good bet he made it but were not 
sure says emlen 
aside from the distinctive touches there are letters in 
evidence between goddard and the brown family which was of such 
importance and munificence that the college of rhode island became 
brown university in their honor a 1763 letter to goddard from 
nicholass brother moses accuses the cabinetmaker of being behind 
on an order and of working for another client when he should have 
been finishing browns furniture 
goddard the quaker wrote back hat respectfully in hand that 
moses should understand he had to keep my boys imployd so i 
hope thou will think better of thy friend he went on to describe 
a chest on chest of drawers and a sweld block front which are 
costly and ornimental 
such a costly and ornamental deskbookcase now known as a 
secretary might have sold for 400 pounds nicholas left at his 
death in 1791 a bookcase with books probably the future 
recordbreaker valued at 95 pounds in the widely fluctuating 
currency but it was high for its times 
there were 10 such desks made in all one burned in a fire 
eight are in museums the brown desk remained in the family from 
the day it was made about 1767 in fact when it was moved to the 
ultimate brown home in providence in 1814 it left there only 
twice both in this century to appear on exhibit 
when he died goddard left all my stock of mahogany to his 
sons to be worked up for the support of my wife and minor 
children a year later the newport mercury carried a sad epitaph 
a notice that said goddard represented insolvent all those 
indebted to said estate are desired to make immediate payment 
and so he faded into obscurity 
the desk meanwhile passed down through the eldest brown sons 
gradually acquiring the status of a family icon says emlen 
a pinnacle of the family fortune the browns had the means to 
change the interior decor every 20 or so years but the desk always 
remained 
the desk for years had received little more notoriety than 
goddard himself then in 1913 it was mentioned in vincent 
lockwoods colonial furniture in america goddard became 
similarly resurrected as were his town and his works 
newport had been invaded by the british during the revolution 
four hundred homes were torn down for firewood in the aftermath 
the town languished its motto being eat it up make it do do 
without in this environment old furniture stayed at home and 
out of antique shops but as the mahogany took on the bloodmaroon 
glowing patina of age the cabinetmakers of newport were recalled 
from their graves as craftsmen whose output in quality design 
and originality was unsurpassed by any other urban or rural 
setting throughout the world 
almost 10 feet in height the goddard desk rose above the 
finicky precious details of the auction house catalog molded 
