<TEXT>
since 1813 it has been turning out equipment and 
weapons for americas fighting men from powder horns to battleship 
guns now with peace breaking out the fortresslike watervliet 
arsenal in upstate new york is once again looking for some other 
kind of work 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
its like ve day all over again for the 
last of the countrys cannon factories 
the easing of sovietamerican tensions in eastern europe and 
expected cutbacks in military spending signal a further eroding of 
demand for artillery made at the 177yearold watervliet arsenal 
near albany the armys biggun shop 
like any military person i welcome peace says col joseph 
mayton jr arsenal commander 
but peace can mean red ink when your job is making the 
heavyhitters that paved the way for american troops in five wars 
and many skirmishes in the last century 
resembling a fortress behind its spiked wroughtiron fence the 
arsenal sells about 150 million in cannons and mortars a year 
mostly to the army it turns out 200 to 250 cannons and mortars a 
month its biggest seller a 120mm gun for the armys abrams m1 
tank which may fall victim to president bushs paredback defense 
budget 
since the last troops left vietnam in 1975 the arsenal has had 
to go out looking for other work says arsenal spokesman john 
swantek 
the plant has made bridges for the marines and its forge can 
fabricate nearly anything out of metal that requires 
highprecision tooling and lowproduction volume mayton says 
one of its hottest new lines are towbars for military vehicles 
a far cry from the 16inch guns the arsenal fashioned for 
battleships in world war ii 
among the last of those 16inch guns the biggest the arsenal 
ever turned out was the one that exploded aboard the uss iowa 
last april killing 47 sailors a navy investigation blamed the 
explosion aboard the battleship on sabotage by a disgruntled sailor 
who died in the blast 
the arsenal no longer makes cannons that big but as long as 
humans know how to make war the demand for big guns will be there 
swantek says 
with all of the euphoria of whats going on in eastern europe 
then something happens like in panama and im sure there were 
watervliet arsenal cannons down there with them mayton says 
about 10 army staffers oversee the arsenal housed in 72 
buildings but the rest of the 2350 workers are civilians an 
arsenal employing about 2700 in rock island ill makes carriages 
for howitzers produced in watervliet 
employment at watervliet peaked at 10000 during world war ii 
a 10year 350 million renovation has brought the latest in 
cannon technology to the arsenal including a laserguided boring 
system and robotics machinery that has automated many tasks 
while that has eliminated the need for some jobs its the 
ebbs and flows of war and peace that dictate employment 
swantek says the arsenal will cut about 100 jobs a year through 
retirements and other voluntary departures so long as the peace 
lasts he says 
a few years before world war ii employment had dropped to about 
140 and there was talk about closing the arsenal and putting 
its 140 acres to other uses says william bradford curator of the 
arsenals museum 
in peacetime people have said say that 140 acres would 
make a nice hospital or a nice school then unfortunately along 
comes another war and people are glad they didnt close it 
swantek says 
the war department opened the arsenal in 1813 to make powder 
horns bullet pouches sword scabbards and other equipment the 
government chose watervliet because of its location near the hudson 
and mohawk rivers from watervliet army supplies could be easily 
shipped to western and northeastern new york where the british 
were likely to attack from forts in canada 
the arsenal was converted to cannon production in the 1880s when 
there were already rumblings about what was to come in europe 
swantek says 
fearing an attack from europe the army ordered large 
longrange cannons placed along the atlantic coast until the 
arsenal began making cannons the armys big guns were mostly made 
by private companies copying european weapons bradford says those 
companies often did shoddy work and to set up its seacoast 
defense the united states needed its own research and production 
area he says 
while the invasion never came the research effort put the 
united states at the front lines of artillery production just in 
time for the wars in europe 
among the arsenals chiefs was col j walker benet father of 
author stephen vincent benet who commanded the arsenal from 1919 
to 1921 the arsenals research center the benet laboratory is 
named for him 
after the wars strained relations between the united states and 
soviet union kept the arsenal forges turning out cannons to defend 
western europe soviet cannon factories churned out their own guns 
to point west 
a drawing hangs in the arsenals quartermilelong big gun 
shop showing a soviet cannon plant superimposed over the 
watervliet facility the soviet plant is more than twice the size 
and its just one of three in the soviet arsenal swantek says 
a past commander at watervliet hung the drawing to show arsenal 
workers that although it was peacetime they still were fighting 
the cold war he says 
with arms production slowing research on improved weapons 
continues at benet laboratory says research director larry 
johnson much of the labs work deals with better production 
methods that could be used in other industries he says 
but the main goal is to build a better cannon which will remain 
a big part of the conventional weapons arsenal for at least 25 
years he says 
theres two ways of settling arguments nuclear deterrents or 
conventional deterrents he says with conventional weapons 
people get hurt but its not terminal to our countries 
if oldfashioned artillery warfare breaks out the arsenal has a 
plan to step up production and mobilize private industry to begin 
producing cannons within a year 
you hope the peace business goes on swantek says but you 
have to wonder how many ebbs and flows will there have been a 
hundred years from now 
