<TEXT>
for 40 years eastern europe has produced goods only the soviet 
union would buy they got back oil raw materials and finished 
products artificial rates were fixed in transferable rubles 
this closed circuit within strictly patrolled borders reduced 
former industrial powers to third world levels with 40 percent of 
the european economic communitys productivity rate at twice the 
energy consumption 
reformminded countries must now wean themselves from the soviet 
union and its socialist trading bloc comecon 
the soviet union and comecon partners agreed in january to work 
toward trade in hard convertible currency but there was sharp 
disagreement on how 
i dont think these countries know what theyre in for said 
jan vanous a specialist on eastern europe at planecon inc a 
washington consulting firm theyll see inflation unemployment 
debt the works 
because east bloc currencies are useless in the west no one 
knows precisely what theyre worth many economists say these 
currencies will have to find their true value in a free market of 
foreign exchange but most agree they are worth a fraction of their 
officially set rates 
this means for example that it could take huge sums of polish 
zlotys czech korunas or hungarian forints to buy the same things 
that smaller amounts of those currencies bought previously 
they will have to break out of the old cycle of you pretend 
to work and we pretend to pay you vanous said it will be 
very difficult 
some eastern european leaders who espouse free enterprise and 
open markets still recoil from the term capitalism 
romanias revolutionary government for example cannot remove 
the social safety net as it picks up the pieces of a potentially 
rich agricultural economy plundered by executed dictator nicolae 
ceausescu 
when the revolution began petre roman said romania would open 
its economy to the world later as prime minister he remarked it 
would be irresponsible to speak of this in detail now 
czechoslovakia is slowly opening without abandoning socialist 
safeguards guided by economists who pushed for reform under the 
communists not only are top managers reluctant to relinquish power 
but many workers fear the adventure of free competition 
we will have a tremendous job breaking up the mafia that runs 
the big state companies said one government adviser who spoke 
on the condition of anonymity i am not sure we can do it 
east germany is trying to intertwine with west germany while 
keeping its socialist character but as people move west from cab 
drivers to physicists plans are in turmoil pressure from bonn is 
accelerating economic integration 
hungarians have experimented with a private sector since the 
early 1980s and have long been open to outside influence today 
budapest looks like a prosperous western capital vaci street 
nearly as swank as paris rue de la paix glitters with wealth its 
mcdonalds is europes busiest 
general motors corp recently committed 150 million to a joint 
venture one of 400 deals struck in the last six months between 
hungarian and foreign companies hungarian officials toured us 
stock exchanges last month in preparation for plans to expand their 
own launched a year ago 
in a desperate imagebuilding move hungary decided to cohost 
the 1995 worlds fair with austria which will cost its strapped 
economy an estimated 25 billion 
laszlo lengyel an influential economic consultant in budapest 
said little has changed for hungarys or eastern europes three 
main classes despite giant political strides 
in hungary wages average 150 a month waiting lists for tiny 
subsidized apartments approach 20 years private homes are 
prohibitively expensive 
while the elites retain power lengyel said a broad class of 
workers sees no prospect for new income beyond controlled wages 
worse many fear layoffs in a new freeforall atmosphere 
a third class of people with second jobs or small businesses on 
the side might take new risks he said but few have contacts 
access to capital or reliable suppliers 
lengyel said a breakthrough may come from european and japanese 
investors who join local entrepreneurs in businesses that control 
their own supply and distribution 
but he said the american approach offering minimal official 
aid and encouraging joint ventures will have limited impact even 
some american diplomats in the region say privately that a country 
which spent trillions to combat communism militarily should risk a 
few billion to defeat it peacefully 
the gdansk shipyard birthplace of the solidarity movement that 
incited the east blocs sweeping changes embodies the challenge 
operations director hans szyc explained he could sell all the 
ships he could make but not without capital foreign investors 
remain cautious and local banks charge 58 percent interest per 
month 
true i am proud of the role this shipyard played in changing 
the whole world szyc said but the problem is not the past 
not today but the future 
