<DOCNO> AP900212-0206 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
eastern european nations face a range of alternatives in the 
search for prototypes to reform their stagnating economies all 
involve dismantling staterun subsidy systems that keep prices 
artificially low unleashing market forces of supply and demand 
and moving toward integration with the rest of the world the 
unprecedented undertaking is fraught with risks moreover none of 
the models advanced so far has been put to an extended test 
below are some of the approaches under discussion 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
stateowned companies would be converted to workerowned 
businesses through the issuance of stock to employees under this 
arrangement the government would give preferential lowinterest 
loans to these businesses repayable over long periods while 
workers would control production expansion research marketing 
hiring and firing employee ownership would preserve the socialist 
ideal of workers controlling their own destinies but in the west 
where variations of this model also have been tried they often 
have resulted in inefficiency and a reluctance by employees to make 
tough decisions needed for their businesses to compete and survive 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
stateowned companies would be sold to existing management 
foreign companies or a combination of both in essentially one bold 
stroke the government would end its role as a giant business 
monopoly theoretically encouraging competition and productivity 
sales of stateowned assets would be financed by lowinterest 
government loans if the buyers are overseas investors the 
government would benefit by an infusion of foreign currency and 
expertise the risks lie in entrenching old managers mostly 
unqualified communist party functionaries the process could create 
enormous resentment by workers who feel little has changed 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
stateowned companies would be restructured into interlocking 
networks of suppliers and lenders that own stakes in each other 
creating an incentive for them to cooperate an automaker for 
example would form a partnership with a steel factory which would 
be partly owned by a bank which in turn would be partly owned by 
the automaker workers would assume a role in helping direct these 
networks and would be protected by labor unions variations of this 
model helped revive the shattered economies of postwar japan and 
west germany but in eastern europes case they raise the 
possibility of entrenching unqualified managers similar to the 
risk presented by the management ownership model 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
stateowned companies would be turned over to the population at 
large either in the form of stock given to all or via an auction 
in which groups of citizens would compete to buy them this 
strategy in many respects is the fairest by giving people an equal 
economic opportunity but it also presents the threat of 
instability and confusion if companies are simply restructured 
into stock portfolios for each citizen no new capital is created 
for the economy to grow 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the government would encourage the creation of smallscale 
private businesses by managers and employees of existing 
stateowned firms this strategy would preserve the states 
dominant economic role indefinitely but would create new sources of 
employment and production the risk lies in the advantages that 
some state enterprises have in access to supplies creating the 
possibility of profiteering and a polarization of classes into rich 
and poor variations of this strategy have been tried on a limited 
basis in china but often have led to official corruption and a 
popular backlash against entrepreneurs who become relatively 
wealthy 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

