<TEXT>
top american and soviet trade officials today 
launched wideranging negotiations aimed at normalizing trade 
between the two superpowers for the first time in nearly a 
halfcentury 
asked if the talks could be accomplished in time for president 
bush and soviet president mikhail s gorbachev to sign a new trade 
treaty at their summit in june us trade representative carla 
hills said we are a very efficient team 
she and deputy trade representative julius katz led the american 
negotiating team while the soviet delegation was headed by yuriy 
n chumakov deputy minister of foreign economic relations 
the agenda for just the first day of consultations listed 15 
areas of discussions the complexity of the negotiations was 
demonstrated by the fact that the us delegation included 19 
officials from six separate government agencies 
officials said the first round of discussions were scheduled to 
last through tuesday with more talks expected at the end of 
february possibly in moscow 
us officials are hoping to wrap up the negotiations in april 
giving plenty of time for drafting the final document that will be 
signed by bush and gorbachev at the washington summit in june 
bush has said he hopes that normalizing trade relations between 
the two nations will boost the soviet economy and lend support to 
the political reforms being undertaken by gorbachev 
thenpresident truman imposed trade restrictions on the soviet 
union in 1947 after relations between the world war ii allies 
deteriorated 
under a ussoviet trade agreement us consumers would see 
lower prices for such popular items as soviet vodka which by one 
estimate could drop in price by 125 a bottle and for luxury 
items such as russian furs 
as part of a trade agreement the united states would grant the 
soviet union most favored nation status qualifying it for the 
lowest tariffs granted to other countries 
currently the soviets are blocked from that status because of 
the 1974 jacksonvanik amendment which penalized the soviets for 
their ban against emigration by soviet jews and other dissidents 
the soviets have liberalized that policy since gorbachev came to 
power and bush has said he will propose to congress a waiver of 
the jacksonvanik tariffs once the soviet parliament passes 
legislation that would put the liberalized policies into law 
the lower tariffs cannot take effect however until there is a 
trade treaty between the two countries 
one primary area of dispute in the trade talks is expected to be 
how the jacksonvanik tariffs will be lifted the bush 
administration would like a threeyear trade agreement with annual 
presidential review and waiver of the high tariffs 
the soviets however would like to see the tariffs removed 
permanently to build confidence among business leaders that trade 
relations will remain stable in coming years 
but such a position is not likely to find political favor in 
congress micah naftalin national director of the union of 
councils for soviet jews said his organization supports the more 
limited oneyear waivers 
we should be giving them what they have earned but we 
shouldnt go overboard he said the country is still 
extraordinarily unstable and we should take it step by step 
the administration seeks to guarantee the protection of 
americanpatented products from piracy an arbitration method to 
settle business disputes and provisions allowing either country to 
impose temporary trade restrictions if a domestic industry suffers 
injury because of an unexpected surge of imports 
under a trade agreement between the two nations the 
administration predicts that twoway trade which last year totaled 
under 5 billion could double or even triple within the next two 
or three years 
but many experts said the administration was being 
overoptimistic in its projections of increased trade given the 
troubles plaguing the soviet economy 
the reforms that have captured world attention so far have all 
been on the political and social level said richard kaufman an 
expert on soviet affairs with the joint economic committee of 
congress i am not all that optimistic about significant 
increases in trade flows until the soviet economy is reformed 
robert cullen editor of sovietamerican trade a newsletter on 
the subject said that even with a trade agreement the 
fundamental barriers between the soviet union and america such as 
not having a convertible ruble are not going to be alleviated 
american farm groups are watching the trade negotiations with 
keen interest threefourths of us export sales to the soviet 
union involve american farm products and the soviets reportedly 
have stated that they will not approve a new grain sales agreement 
with the united states until they are granted lower tariffs 
</TEXT>
