<TEXT>
the first trial began monday in the guinness 
affair stock manipulation case the unprecedented whitecollar 
scandal that rocked british business after the multibilliondollar 
takeover of distillers co by brewing giant guinness plc 
eight men including guinness former chairman ernest saunders 
have been accused of involvement in a scheme to purchase guinness 
shares during the 1986 takeover fight for distillers a scotch 
whisky and gin maker in an attempt to boost guinness stock price 
the defendants allegedly aimed to make guinness 43 billion 
cash and stock bid more attractive than a rival offer from 
supermarket operator argyll group plc 
guinness succeeded in april 1986 in what was britains largest 
takeover ever but in december of that year the department of 
trade and industry announced it was investigating the deal and the 
alleged financial wrongdoing started coming to light 
the defendants in the first trial which is expected to last up 
to six months are saunders 54 gerald ronson the 50yearold 
chairman of the diversified conglomerate heron international plc 
former stockbroker anthony parnes 44 and millionaire financier 
and arts patron sir jack lyons 74 
they face a total of 35 charges on such counts as stock 
manipulation theft false accounting and destruction of documents 
the four men briefly exchanged words as they took their places 
on swivel chairs behind moveable desks in southwark crown court 
a jury of seven men and five women is to hear the case the 
trial judge sir denis henry adjourned the case until tuesday to 
give the jurors time to put their affairs in order 
the judge ruled last september that because of its complexity 
the case should be split into two consecutive trials 
in the second trial not scheduled to begin before october 
saunders will be joined by roger seelig 44 former morgan grenfell 
and co ltd corporate finance director lord patrick spens 47 
former director of corporate finance at the merchant bank henry 
ansbacher and co ltd and david mayhew 48 who continues as 
senior corporate finance partner of the investment firm cazenove 
and co 
the seven men have pleaded innocent to the charges and each is 
free on 850000 bail 
the eighth man charged is thomas ward an american attorney who 
also has denied wrongdoing british police are seeking wards 
extradition from the united states 
saunders who maintains that he is a scapegoat appears as a 
broken public figure openly bitter about trial delays the 
