<TEXT>
nelson mandelas declaration 
of support monday for nationalization of gold mines and other key 
assets sent shockwaves through south africas business world 
mandelas statement on his first full day of freedom sent gold 
shares down 4 percent on the johannesburg stock exchange the 
financial rand a special currency used to encourage foreign 
investment plummeted 10 percent 
the reaction apparently did not extend overseas gold prices 
rose in europe and the united states 
mandela told a news conference he fully supports the economic 
plan of his african national congress for a staterun economy 
including nationalization of mines and other major pillars of the 
economy 
the nationalization of mines is a fundamental policy of the 
anc mandela said i believe the anc is quite correct in this 
attitude 
businesses also were unnerved by mandelas statements that he 
supports armed struggle to end whiteminority rule and destroy the 
apartheid system mandela also stressed his desire for peace and 
said whites had nothing to fear from blacks under a true democratic 
system 
the remarks punctured optimism in the business community that 
had been generated by president fw de klerks announcement feb 2 
of reforms to pave the way for talks with blacks on peacefully 
ending white minority rule the stock market and other economic 
indicators rose after de klerks speech 
mandelas pronouncements were causing jitters and 
uncertainty said an economist at a major bank who requested 
anonymity 
the black leaders stance will definitely have a negative 
effect on foreign perceptions of investment in south africa on 
local business confidence and on private fixed investment the 
economist said 
whites control the economy and white business and political 
leaders say any future powersharing deal with blacks must rest on 
a free enterprise system the white business community fears 
nationalization will cripple the economy 
business leaders still hope de klerks reforms and concessions 
will convince western countries to abandon or ease the sanctions 
imposed on south africa in recent years as a protest against 
apartheid 
british prime minister margaret thatcher a longtime opponent of 
sanctions dropped academic and cultural embargoes when de klerk 
legalized the anc earlier this month and she now wants to end a 
ban on new investment 
us president george bush has said his government will review 
existing sanctions against south africa but a final decision would 
require congressional approval 
</TEXT>
