grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly 
higher monday on the chicago board of trade bolstered by 
perceptions of shrinking supplies and prospects for new grain sales 
to the soviet union 
in a monthly report released after the close of trading friday 
the usda projected the nations corn stockpile at 148 billion 
bushels by aug 31 the end of the 198990 marketing year that 
compares with the january estimate of 161 billion bushels and last 
years ending stocks of 193 billion 
the usda pegged us wheat stocks at 443 million bushels by may 
31 the end of the wheat marketing year compared with a january 
estimate of 468 million bushels and last years ending stocks of 
698 million 
both estimates were below trade expectations the aug 31 
soybean projection of 335 million bushels unchanged from january 
was near expectations 
traders also were attuned to the opening monday in washington of 
ussoviet trade talks which could lead to the united states 
granting the soviet union mostfavorednation trade status 
allowing freer trade between the superpowers 
at the close wheat futures were unchanged to 2 cents higher 
with the contract for delivery in march at 388 a bushel corn 
