<TEXT>
united airlines labor unions who are seeking 
employee ownership of parent ual corp have approached at least 
one candidate to replace ual chairman stephen m wolf according to 
a report published monday 
the chicago suntimes reported that richard ravitch former 
chairman of bowery savings bank of new york and onetime head of new 
yorks transit authority said he had held very preliminary 
discussions with union representatives 
ravitch also said he had the impression the union group was 
talking with others about taking wolfs job according to the 
newspaper 
attempts by the associated press to contact ravitch were not 
immediately successful a receptionist at his new york office said 
ravitch was out of town but would not reveal his whereabouts 
there has been no indication that wolf would resign from 
chicagobased ual which he has headed since december 1987 as part 
of any employee buyout deal between the unions and the companys 
board of directors 
but the union group representing uniteds pilots machinists 
and flight attendants is believed to be hoping to dump wolf and 
chief financial officer jack pope and recruit a new management team 
before approaching banks for loans to finance a buyout 
union and ual board representatives have been negotiating the 
terms of a formal buyout bid and are expected to report on their 
progress at a feb 22 board meeting 
neither a ual spokesman nor spokesmen for the three unions would 
comment on the suntimes report 
a source within the union group who spoke on condition of 
anonymity said the management issue has not been decided but he 
said i think its probably fair to say that everyone wouldnt 
mind looking elsewhere 
wolfs role in an employeeowned ual was not covered in a buyout 
proposal outlined by the unions last month nor was the price of 
the 75 percent stake that the workers want to buy 
some airline analysts believe dumping wolf would be a mistake 
despite his history of fractious relations with the unions 
they say wolfs experience in turning around the financial 
fortunes of the former republic airlines and flying tiger 
airfreight carrier before coming to ual make him a good leader for 
united which has fallen behind american airlines in ridership in 
recent years after long leading the industry 
analyst louis marckesano of janney montgomery scott inc in 
philadelphia said the subject of dumping wolf came up at a recent 
meeting of airline analysts most of whom thought it would be big 
dumb thing the unions may be trying to do 
uals stock lost 4 to close at 13250 monday in new york stock 
exchange trading 
