<TEXT>
a federal bankruptcy judge on monday gave 
eastern airlines another eight days to file its proposed plan of 
reorganization after several parties in the proceeding said 
progress has been made toward agreement on a plan 
us bankruptcy judge burton r lifland granted easterns 
request for the extension to feb 20 of the deadline for filing 
its bankruptcy reorganization plan during that time other parties 
such as creditors cannot submit competing proposals 
miamibased eastern has been restructuring under bankruptcy 
court supervision since a grueling strike began last march 4 the 
airline asked the court last week for a 30day extension but 
reduced its request before mondays hearing indicating that 
eastern and its major creditors may have moved toward compromise on 
a plan 
david i shapiro the courtappointed examiner overseeing 
easterns chapter 11 proceeding supported the request and told 
lifland that substantial progress is being made in negotiations 
between the airline and its creditors 
shapiro said last week he would fight liquidation of eastern as 
rumors circulated that texas air corp easterns owner would opt 
for a chapter 7 liquidation 
the committee representing unsecured creditors also supported 
easterns petition 
representatives of preferred shareholders who recently 
advocated liquidation or outright sale supported the airlines 
request for more time however 
in papers filed earlier in bankruptcy court a committee 
representing tthe preferred holders said it had lost faith in 
easterns management because it was cannibalizing the airline 
by selling vital assets 
the preferred shareholders criticized easterns latest 
reorganization proposal recently diclosed publicly which proposes 
to pay them no more than 10 cents on the dollar in the form of new 
stock 
we are examining all of our various options were hopeful we 
can come up with a solution robert miller an attorney for the 
preferred shareholders committee said after the hearing 
the new plan also calls for paying unsecured creditors only 10 
percent of their debts in cash when the airline emerges from 
bankruptcy protection and 70 percent more over the following 10 
years without interest 
in return for accepting partial repayment texas air would give 
the unsecured creditors 40 percent of easterns equity 
lawyers representing the air line pilots association and the 
machinists union opposed easterns request 
the pilots and flight attendants abandoned their sympathy 
strikes just before thanksgiving but eastern had since rebuilt as 
a smaller carrier and hired mostly nonunion workers to replace the 
strikers the machinists union remains on strike against the 
carrier 
mondays extension was the fourth granted by lifland to eastern 
since the bankruptcy proceeding began last march 9 
