<TEXT>
eastern europe governments attempting to move 
away from communism should seek to stabilize their budgets 
inflation and exchange rates before dealing with problems of trade 
industry and labor a banking group advised monday 
nevertheless the other problems also have to be tackled soon 
said a report of the institute of international finance an 
association of major banks throughout the world 
the problem of successfully liberalizing a distorted economy 
can be likened to the problem of teaching a baby elephant to stand 
up it said 
the order in which it straightens its legs is important only 
to the extent that it influences the elephants ability to 
straighten them at all 
titled financial sector reform its role in growth and 
development the study is based on the experience of chile 
greece malaysia new zealand and tunisia 
it said detailed priorities should vary from place to place 
in some third world countries such as malaysia the study found 
the main task was to build institutions where few or none existed 
to develop skilled people and to build the basis for a modern 
economy 
most heavily indebted latin american countries had followed 
misguided policies for many years the study said adding that at 
various times countries such as new zealand tunisia greece and 
chile have made similar mistakes 
the priorities listed by the study included 
getting control and stabilizing taxation government borrowing 
and spending credit and prices 
decentralizing decisions to get them out of the hands of 
bureaucrasts and politicians and giving more authority to people 
with information and incentives 
developing a situation for healthy markets so that prices 
reflect cost and scarcity giving people the incentive to put their 
money into useful investments 
adopting an exchange rate that reflects actual value on the 
market getting rid of taxes on exports high duties on imports and 
preference for stateowned business 
reorganizing stateowned business 
the report warned that delay in financial changes may lead to 
high inflation and instability in other parts of the economy 
these issues are particularly important to the design of 
programs in central and eastern europe said horst schulmann 
managing director of the institute 
pushing financial changes including control of the government 
budget and convertibility of local currencies into hard money also 
is the priority for jeffrey sachs the harvard university professor 
who is advising poland and yugoslavia sachs said last week that 
poland is already beginning to see results in lower food prices 
the yugoslavs have also introduced full convertibility of the 
dinar as of jan 1 backed by billions of dollars of foreign 
