<TEXT>
south korea will run a trade deficit 
of 33 billion this year the worst in nine years the korea 
foreign trade association predicted tuesday 
the figure compared with a government projected deficit of 2 
billion both figures were on a customs clearance basis 
the national traders group expected 663 billion in exports 
this year up 64 percent from 623 billion in 1989 while 
predicting 696 billion in imports up 135 percent from 613 
billion in 1989 
the government projected 66 billion in exports and 68 billion 
in imports for 1990 
association officials said exports are expected to recover 
somewhat in the second quarter of this year but the growth is 
likely to be far outpaced by surging imports 
after years of substantial trade deficits korea scored its 
first annual trade surplus in 1986 amounting to 31 billion 
the countrys trade surplus rose to a record 88 billion in 
1988 but plunged to 1 billion in 1989 because of the loss of 
export competitiveness affected by the korean currencys 
appreciation steep wage hikes and labor unrest in the past three 
years 
the association said its projection was based on assumption that 
the korean currency will be devalued by 56 percent during this 
year to 720 won to the dollar accompanied by moderate wage hikes 
and few labor disputes 
the group called on the government to take substantial steps to 
reinvigorate exports the government so far has refused to take any 
drastic measures on exchange rates and bank loan interest rates for 
fear of high inflation and instead has called for structural reform 
of korean industries 
</TEXT>
