<DOCNO> AP900212-0249 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the west german government will make an 
official offer tuesday to east germany to form a monetary union of 
the two countries diplomats of the european community said monday 
west german finance minister theo waigel revealed the move at a 
meeting of finance ministers of the european community the 
12nation trading bloc according to officials 
no details of the plan were released 
east german premier hans modrow was scheduled to travel to bonn 
to meet with west german officials on tuesday and wednesday 
community officials had anxiously awaited waigels remarks 
because of concern about the effect of a monetary union of the two 
germanys on the rest of western europe which is planning its own 
monetary reform as part of its plans to remove trade barriers by 
1992 
a german monetary union no doubt would involve circulation of 
west germanys strong mark currency in the east 
communist east germany has seen its centrally planned economy 
deteriorate rapidly since the border between the two countries 
opened late last year thousands of east germans have poured into 
their western neighbor 
i fully understand bonns position to accelerate its 
economic and monetary union with east germany said dutch 
finance minister wim kok but brussels must be the place where we 
help determine germanys position on that 
i have full confidence in the fact that germangerman economic 
and monetary integration will be firmly anchored in wider european 
consultations he told reporters i find that crucial 
west germanys economy based on a freemarket system is the 
most powerful in the european community many of the west european 
currencies are closely tied to the west german mark and the ec 
countries have been working on plans to form a common currency for 
their members 
irish finance minister albert reynolds said waigel indicated 
the german government will make an offer to east germany tomorrow 
on closer integration for monetary union ireland currently holds 
the communitys rotating sixmonth presidency 
he said waigel promised to keep the community fully informed 
of developments 
a diplomatic source demanding anonymity said jacques delors 
president of the communitys executive body raised questions about 
how the german monetary union would affect the trading blocs 
monetary system 
an internal report by the european commission the executive 
body said that immediate monetary union would create a strong 
confidence factor but it also cautioned that a quick marriage 
would irrevocably link west germany to east germany 
any turbulences and setbacks in east germany would be 
transmitted to the west german economy and thereby also to the 
community said the study 
these turbulences and frictions seem however almost 
unavoidable it said it should not be forgotten that almost 
the whole east german population has had no direct experience 
with democracy and a market economy 
waigel told german reporters that he delivered a message to the 
finance ministers from west german chancellor helmut kohl who said 
his country remains committed to the communitys campaign to form 
an economic and monetary union 
kohl also said the bonn government would discuss its unity plans 
with all community institutions 
waigel said no date was mentioned for a german monetary union 
because it depended on discussions this week with modrow and the 
outcome of the march 18 elections in east germany 
he also noted the east german economy is onetenth the size of 
west germanys the dimension of the integration issue should not 
be exaggerated he said 
i tried to convince my colleagues that the challenge can be 
met by west germany if one takes a midterm view that is from 
five to 10 years he told reporters 
</TEXT>
